Create the `RouteErrorFallback` component that renders inside the app shell when a route-level error occurs (loader failure, component throw). The sidebar and header remain visible; only the `<Outlet />` area shows this fallback.

## File to Create

**`apps/client/src/layers/shared/ui/route-error-fallback.tsx`**

```typescript
import { useRouter } from '@tanstack/react-router';
import type { ErrorComponentProps } from '@tanstack/react-router';
import { AlertTriangle } from 'lucide-react';
import { Button } from './button';

/**
 * Default error fallback for route-level errors.
 *
 * Renders inside the app shell — sidebar and header remain visible.
 * Uses `router.invalidate()` for retry (not `reset()`) because `reset()`
 * does not re-run loaders. See TanStack/router#2539.
 */
export function RouteErrorFallback({ error }: ErrorComponentProps) {
  const router = useRouter();

  return (
    <div className="flex h-full flex-col items-center justify-center gap-6 p-8">
      <AlertTriangle className="text-muted-foreground size-10" />
      <div className="flex flex-col items-center gap-2 text-center">
        <h2 className="text-foreground text-lg font-semibold">Something went wrong</h2>
        <p className="text-muted-foreground max-w-md text-sm">{error.message}</p>
      </div>

      {import.meta.env.DEV && error.stack && (
        <details className="border-border/50 max-w-2xl rounded-md border px-4 py-2">
          <summary className="text-muted-foreground cursor-pointer text-xs">
            Stack trace (dev only)
          </summary>
          <pre className="text-muted-foreground mt-2 overflow-x-auto text-xs whitespace-pre-wrap">
            {error.stack}
          </pre>
        </details>
      )}

      <div className="flex gap-3">
        <Button variant="outline" size="sm" onClick={() => router.invalidate()}>
          Retry
        </Button>
        <Button variant="ghost" size="sm" onClick={() => router.navigate({ to: '/' })}>
          Go to Dashboard
        </Button>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Test File to Create

**`apps/client/src/layers/shared/ui/__tests__/route-error-fallback.test.tsx`**

Test cases to implement:

1. **renders error message from error prop** — Pass `{ error: new Error('Test failure'), reset: vi.fn(), info: { componentStack: '' } }` and assert `screen.getByText('Test failure')` is in the document.
2. **renders "Something went wrong" heading** — Assert `screen.getByText('Something went wrong')` exists.
3. **renders Retry button** — Assert `screen.getByRole('button', { name: /retry/i })` exists.
4. **renders "Go to Dashboard" link** — Assert `screen.getByRole('button', { name: /go to dashboard/i })` exists.
5. **calls router.invalidate() when Retry is clicked** — Mock `useRouter` from `@tanstack/react-router` returning `{ invalidate: vi.fn(), navigate: vi.fn() }`. Click the Retry button and assert `invalidate` was called.
6. **shows stack trace in dev mode** — With `import.meta.env.DEV` mocked to `true`, pass an error with a `.stack` property. Assert the `<details>` element with "Stack trace (dev only)" text is present.
7. **hides stack trace in production mode** — With `import.meta.env.DEV` mocked to `false`, pass an error with a `.stack` property. Assert no "Stack trace" text is present.

Mocking approach:
```typescript
// @vitest-environment jsdom
import { describe, it, expect, vi, beforeEach } from 'vitest';
import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react';
import userEvent from '@testing-library/user-event';

const mockInvalidate = vi.fn();
const mockNavigate = vi.fn();
vi.mock('@tanstack/react-router', () => ({
  useRouter: () => ({ invalidate: mockInvalidate, navigate: mockNavigate }),
}));

import { RouteErrorFallback } from '../route-error-fallback';
```

For the dev/prod mode tests, use `vi.stubGlobal` or mock `import.meta.env.DEV` via `vi.stubEnv('DEV', 'true')` / `vi.stubEnv('DEV', '')` depending on Vitest configuration. Alternatively, test the dev-mode behavior in the default test environment (Vite dev mode sets `import.meta.env.DEV = true` by default in Vitest).

## Acceptance Criteria

- Component renders AlertTriangle icon, heading, error message, Retry button, and Go to Dashboard button
- Retry button calls `router.invalidate()` (NOT `reset()`)
- Go to Dashboard button calls `router.navigate({ to: '/' })`
- Stack trace is shown in dev mode via a collapsible `<details>` element
- Stack trace is hidden in production
- All 7 test cases pass
- Component has TSDoc comment explaining the `invalidate()` vs `reset()` decision

