Create the `AppCrashFallback` component — the last-resort crash fallback for catastrophic errors. This component has a CRITICAL CONSTRAINT: it uses ZERO imports from the app bundle (no shadcn, no Tailwind, no router, no context). Only inline styles. If context providers crashed, any dependency on them would also crash.

## File to Create

**`apps/client/src/layers/shared/ui/app-crash-fallback.tsx`**

```typescript
import type { FallbackProps } from 'react-error-boundary';

/**
 * Last-resort crash fallback for catastrophic errors.
 *
 * Uses inline styles only — no shadcn, no Tailwind, no app context.
 * If providers crashed, any dependency on them would also crash.
 * The only recovery action is a full page reload.
 */
export function AppCrashFallback({ error }: FallbackProps) {
  return (
    <div
      style={{
        display: 'flex',
        flexDirection: 'column',
        alignItems: 'center',
        justifyContent: 'center',
        height: '100dvh',
        padding: '2rem',
        backgroundColor: '#09090b',
        color: '#d4d4d8',
        fontFamily:
          'ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, "SF Mono", Menlo, Consolas, monospace',
      }}
    >
      <p style={{ fontSize: '1rem', fontWeight: 600, marginBottom: '0.5rem' }}>
        DorkOS encountered an unexpected error.
      </p>
      <p style={{ fontSize: '0.75rem', opacity: 0.6, maxWidth: '32rem', textAlign: 'center' }}>
        {error.message}
      </p>

      {import.meta.env.DEV && error.stack && (
        <details
          style={{
            marginTop: '1rem',
            maxWidth: '48rem',
            width: '100%',
            border: '1px solid #27272a',
            borderRadius: '0.375rem',
            padding: '0.5rem 1rem',
          }}
        >
          <summary
            style={{ fontSize: '0.75rem', cursor: 'pointer', opacity: 0.5 }}
          >
            Stack trace (dev only)
          </summary>
          <pre
            style={{
              fontSize: '0.625rem',
              opacity: 0.4,
              marginTop: '0.5rem',
              overflowX: 'auto',
              whiteSpace: 'pre-wrap',
            }}
          >
            {error.stack}
          </pre>
        </details>
      )}

      <button
        onClick={() => window.location.reload()}
        style={{
          marginTop: '1.5rem',
          padding: '0.5rem 1rem',
          fontSize: '0.875rem',
          backgroundColor: 'transparent',
          color: '#d4d4d8',
          border: '1px solid #3f3f46',
          borderRadius: '0.375rem',
          cursor: 'pointer',
          fontFamily: 'inherit',
        }}
        onMouseOver={(e) => {
          (e.target as HTMLButtonElement).style.backgroundColor = '#18181b';
        }}
        onMouseOut={(e) => {
          (e.target as HTMLButtonElement).style.backgroundColor = 'transparent';
        }}
      >
        Reload DorkOS
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Note: The only import is `type { FallbackProps } from 'react-error-boundary'` which is a TYPE-only import (erased at compile time, zero runtime dependency).

## Test File to Create

**`apps/client/src/layers/shared/ui/__tests__/app-crash-fallback.test.tsx`**

Test cases to implement:

1. **renders error message from error prop** — Pass `{ error: new Error('Provider crashed'), resetErrorBoundary: vi.fn() }` as props. Assert `screen.getByText('Provider crashed')` is present.
2. **renders "Reload DorkOS" button** — Assert `screen.getByRole('button', { name: /reload dorkos/i })` exists.
3. **calls window.location.reload() when button is clicked** — Mock `window.location.reload` with `vi.fn()` (use `Object.defineProperty` to make it writable). Click the button and assert `reload` was called.
4. **shows stack trace in dev mode** — With `import.meta.env.DEV` as `true`, pass an error with `.stack`. Assert "Stack trace (dev only)" text is present.
5. **hides stack trace in production mode** — With `import.meta.env.DEV` as `false`, assert no "Stack trace" text appears.
6. **renders with inline styles only (no className attributes on any element)** — This is the CRITICAL test validating the no-Tailwind constraint. After rendering, query all elements inside the container and assert NONE of them have a `className` attribute:

```typescript
it('renders with inline styles only (no className attributes on any element)', () => {
  const { container } = render(
    <AppCrashFallback error={new Error('test')} resetErrorBoundary={vi.fn()} />
  );
  const allElements = container.querySelectorAll('*');
  allElements.forEach((el) => {
    expect(el.getAttribute('class')).toBeNull();
  });
});
```

Mocking approach:
```typescript
// @vitest-environment jsdom
import { describe, it, expect, vi, beforeEach } from 'vitest';
import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react';
import userEvent from '@testing-library/user-event';
import { AppCrashFallback } from '../app-crash-fallback';
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- Component renders with ZERO `className` props — inline styles only
- Only import is `type { FallbackProps }` (type-only, erased at compile time)
- Dark background (#09090b), monospace font, matching the DorkOS aesthetic
- "Reload DorkOS" button calls `window.location.reload()`
- Button has hover effect via inline `onMouseOver`/`onMouseOut` handlers
- Stack trace shown only in dev mode
- All 6 test cases pass
- Component has TSDoc comment explaining the inline-styles-only constraint

Modify `apps/client/src/main.tsx` to add React 19 `createRoot` error hooks (telemetry) and wrap `<Root />` in the top-level `ErrorBoundary` from `react-error-boundary`.

## File to Modify

**`apps/client/src/main.tsx`**

### Changes

1. **Add imports** at the top of the file:
```typescript
import { ErrorBoundary } from 'react-error-boundary';
import { AppCrashFallback } from '@/layers/shared/ui/app-crash-fallback';
```

Note: Import `AppCrashFallback` directly from its file path (not the barrel) to avoid pulling the entire shared/ui barrel into the critical error path. This is intentional — if the barrel itself has an issue, the crash fallback still works.

2. **Replace the existing `createRoot` call** (currently at the bottom of the file, around line 131):

Current code:
```typescript
ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById('root')!).render(
  <React.StrictMode>
    <Root />
  </React.StrictMode>
);
```

New code:
```typescript
ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById('root')!, {
  onCaughtError: (error, errorInfo) => {
    // Fires when an ErrorBoundary catches — fallback UI is already showing
    console.error('[dorkos:caught]', error, errorInfo.componentStack);
  },
  onUncaughtError: (error, errorInfo) => {
    // Fires when no ErrorBoundary caught it — full app crash
    console.error('[dorkos:uncaught]', error, errorInfo.componentStack);
  },
}).render(
  <React.StrictMode>
    <ErrorBoundary FallbackComponent={AppCrashFallback}>
      <Root />
    </ErrorBoundary>
  </React.StrictMode>
);
```

### Key Design Decisions

- `onCaughtError` and `onUncaughtError` are React 19 telemetry hooks. They render no UI — they are extension points for future observability (Sentry, PostHog).
- The `ErrorBoundary` wraps `<Root />` INSIDE `<React.StrictMode>` so StrictMode's double-render behavior is preserved.
- `AppCrashFallback` uses inline styles only, so it works even if Tailwind/providers crashed.
- The `ErrorBoundary` is the outermost boundary — it catches errors from QueryClientProvider, TransportProvider, RouterProvider, and all descendants.

## Acceptance Criteria

- `createRoot` is called with `onCaughtError` and `onUncaughtError` options
- Both hooks log to `console.error` with `[dorkos:caught]` / `[dorkos:uncaught]` prefixes
- `<Root />` is wrapped in `<ErrorBoundary FallbackComponent={AppCrashFallback}>`
- `ErrorBoundary` is inside `<React.StrictMode>` (not outside)
- No other changes to `main.tsx` — the `Root` function, `DevtoolsToggle`, `getApiBaseUrl`, `extensionDeps`, etc. remain unchanged
- App compiles and runs without errors

Modify `apps/client/src/router.tsx` to set `defaultErrorComponent` and `defaultNotFoundComponent` on the router, and update the root route's `notFoundComponent`.

## File to Modify

**`apps/client/src/router.tsx`**

### Changes

1. **Add imports** at the top of the file:
```typescript
import { RouteErrorFallback } from '@/layers/shared/ui';
import { NotFoundFallback } from '@/layers/shared/ui';
```

Or combined:
```typescript
import { RouteErrorFallback, NotFoundFallback } from '@/layers/shared/ui';
```

2. **Update the root route** — replace the inline `notFoundComponent` (currently `() => <div>404 — Page not found</div>` on line 26):

Current code:
```typescript
const rootRoute = createRootRouteWithContext<RouterContext>()({
  component: () => <Outlet />,
  notFoundComponent: () => <div>404 — Page not found</div>,
});
```

New code:
```typescript
const rootRoute = createRootRouteWithContext<RouterContext>()({
  component: () => <Outlet />,
  notFoundComponent: NotFoundFallback,
});
```

3. **Add defaults to `createRouter`** in the `createAppRouter` function (currently at line 151-157):

Current code:
```typescript
export function createAppRouter(queryClient: QueryClient) {
  return createRouter({
    routeTree,
    context: { queryClient },
    defaultPreload: 'intent',
  });
}
```

New code:
```typescript
export function createAppRouter(queryClient: QueryClient) {
  return createRouter({
    routeTree,
    context: { queryClient },
    defaultPreload: 'intent',
    defaultErrorComponent: RouteErrorFallback,
    defaultNotFoundComponent: NotFoundFallback,
  });
}
```

### Key Design Decisions

- `defaultErrorComponent: RouteErrorFallback` applies to ALL routes that don't define their own `errorComponent`. This replaces TanStack Router's default red stack trace dump.
- `defaultNotFoundComponent: NotFoundFallback` applies to all routes that don't define their own `notFoundComponent`.
- The root route's explicit `notFoundComponent: NotFoundFallback` catches structural 404s (URL matches no route at all).
- TanStack Router's internal `CatchBoundary` uses `router.state.loadedAt` as a reset key — the error boundary auto-clears on any navigation.

## Acceptance Criteria

- Root route uses `NotFoundFallback` instead of the inline `<div>404 — Page not found</div>`
- `createRouter` has `defaultErrorComponent: RouteErrorFallback` and `defaultNotFoundComponent: NotFoundFallback`
- No other changes to route definitions, search schemas, or loaders
- Navigating to `/nonexistent-path` shows `NotFoundFallback` inside the app shell
- A route-level error shows `RouteErrorFallback` inside the app shell
- App compiles and runs without errors

Modify `apps/client/src/layers/shared/lib/query-client.ts` to add `QueryCache` and `MutationCache` instances with global `onError` handlers for telemetry and toast notifications.

## File to Modify

**`apps/client/src/layers/shared/lib/query-client.ts`**

### Full Replacement

Replace the entire file content with:

```typescript
/**
 * Singleton TanStack Query client — shared across the app and importable
 * by non-React code (e.g. the SSE reconnection handler) via dynamic import.
 *
 * Error handling strategy:
 * - QueryCache.onError: Logs all query errors for telemetry. Shows toast only
 *   when the query opts in via `meta.showToastOnError`.
 * - MutationCache.onError: Shows a generic toast for all failed mutations.
 *   Individual mutations can override with their own `onError` callback.
 *
 * throwOnError is NOT set globally — it's opt-in per query:
 * - Background/polling queries: never throw (stale data > crashed page)
 * - Critical page content: use throwOnError + QueryErrorResetBoundary
 * - Optional widget data: handle isError inline in the component
 *
 * @module shared/lib/query-client
 */
import { QueryClient, QueryCache, MutationCache } from '@tanstack/react-query';
import { toast } from 'sonner';

import { QUERY_TIMING } from './constants';

/** Application-wide QueryClient singleton. */
export const queryClient = new QueryClient({
  queryCache: new QueryCache({
    onError: (error, query) => {
      console.error('[dorkos:query-error]', {
        queryKey: query.queryKey,
        error: error.message,
      });
      if (query.meta?.showToastOnError) {
        toast.error((query.meta.errorLabel as string) ?? 'Failed to load data');
      }
    },
  }),
  mutationCache: new MutationCache({
    onError: (error) => {
      console.error('[dorkos:mutation-error]', { error: error.message });
      toast.error('Action failed. Please try again.');
    },
  }),
  defaultOptions: {
    queries: {
      staleTime: QUERY_TIMING.DEFAULT_STALE_TIME_MS,
      retry: QUERY_TIMING.DEFAULT_RETRY,
    },
  },
});
```

### Key Design Decisions

- `QueryCache.onError` fires for ALL query errors. It always logs for telemetry. It only shows a toast when the individual query opts in via `meta.showToastOnError` — this prevents noisy toasts from background/polling queries.
- `MutationCache.onError` shows a generic toast for ALL failed mutations. TanStack Query v5 calls `MutationCache.onError` first, then the mutation-level `onError`. Existing per-mutation handlers (e.g., in `ScheduleRow.tsx`, `RunHistoryPanel.tsx`) continue to work. The global handler is a safety net.
- `throwOnError` is NOT set globally. It remains opt-in per query.
- The `sonner` import is already available in the project (used elsewhere for toast notifications).
- The `toast` import adds `sonner` as a runtime dependency of this module. Since `query-client.ts` is already imported early in the app boot sequence, this is acceptable.

### Interaction with existing mutations

Some existing mutations already show specific toast messages via their own `onError` callbacks. The global `MutationCache.onError` will also fire, potentially resulting in a duplicate toast. This is acceptable for the initial implementation — if a mutation wants to suppress the global toast in the future, it can set `meta.skipGlobalToast: true` and the handler can be updated to check for it.

## Acceptance Criteria

- `QueryCache` is constructed with an `onError` handler that logs `[dorkos:query-error]` and conditionally shows a toast
- `MutationCache` is constructed with an `onError` handler that logs `[dorkos:mutation-error]` and shows a toast
- `QUERY_TIMING.DEFAULT_STALE_TIME_MS` and `QUERY_TIMING.DEFAULT_RETRY` defaults are preserved unchanged
- The module-level TSDoc is updated with the error handling strategy documentation
- `sonner` is imported for `toast.error()` calls
- App compiles and runs without errors

